===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*lot||free; release; slip; dislocate}} (STEDT under PTB *g/s-lwat; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).
:Within Chinese, cognate with:
:*{{och-l|蛻|id=2|exuviae (skin cast off during molting)}}
:*{{och-l|愉|relax > happy, pleased}}
:*{{och-l|悅|id=1|contented}}
:*{{och-l|說|id=2|to speak, to explain}}
:*{{och-l|說|id=1|to persuade}}
:*{{och-l|偷|to steal}}
:*{{och-l|奪|to rob, to snatch|tr=*Cə.lˁot}};
:Outside Chinese, cognate with {{cog|bo|གློད་པ||loosen, relax, slacken}}, {{cog|bo|ཧློད་པ|t=loose, relaxed}}, {{cog|lep|ᰒᰤᰦᰳ|tr=flját}}, {{m|lep|ᰒᰤᰩᰳ|tr=fljót}}, {{cog|my|လွှတ်}}, {{cog|my|ချွတ်}}.
In its use in Northern Wu languages, such as [[w:Shanghainese|Shanghainese]], [[w:Suzhou dialect|Suzhounese]], and [[w:Ningbo dialect|Ningbonese]], as well as [[w:Lower Yangtze Mandarin|Lower Yangtze Mandarin]], it is likely from a grammaticalisation of the verb. Compare with {{zh-l|落|tr=-}} ([[w:Wuxi|Wuxi]], [[w:Changzhou|Changzhou]]) and {{zh-l|掉|tr=-}} ([[w:Haining|Haining]], [[w:Danyang|Danyang]]).

